/*
What is pointer arithmetic?
Pointer arithmetic refers to the operations that can be performed on pointers, such as addition and subtraction. When we perform pointer arithmetic, the pointer is moved by a certain number of bytes based on the size of the data type it points to. For example, if we have an integer pointer and we add 1 to it, the pointer will move to the next integer in memory, which is typically 4 bytes away (assuming a 32-bit system). Similarly, if we have a character pointer and we add 1 to it, the pointer will move to the next character in memory, which is typically 1 byte away. Pointer arithmetic allows us to navigate through arrays and other data structures efficiently. 
